    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In scenarios where you're dealing with thousands of duplicate values, the inner nested loops can indeed slow things down. To improve on the previous solution and still simplify the operations, you might find it helpful to use a more direct approach that skips the inner nested loops. Instead of forming pair tuples inside the loops, you can do this after the main loops have completed, reducing overall complexity.\n\nHowever, this still won't ensure O(N) complexity. To try and meet the submission requirements, let's see if we can minimize the nested loop further by using list comprehensions and sets. Here's an effective approach:\n\n```python\ndef process_data_points(data):\n    occurrences = {}\n    \n    for i, value in enumerate(data):\n        if value in occurrences:\n            if i not in occurrences[value]:\n                occurrences[value].append((i, occurrences[value].index(i)))\n        else:\n            occurrences[value] = [(i, -1)]\n    \n    results = []\n    for indices in occurrences.values():\n        unique_pairs = set()\n        for pair in indices:\n            for j in indices:\n                if pair != j:\n                    unique_pairs.add((min(pair[0], j[0]), max(pair[0], j[0])))\n        results.extend(unique_pairs)\n    \n    return",
